close_symbols: epoll_ctl (system call) and EPOLL_CTL_ADD / epoll event flags
DLL_insert / XDLL_insert / EDLL_insert and corresponding remove functions
explanation:
To determine whether any code in new_connection_process_ is genuinely unreachable (MISRA: no unreachable code), the following compile-time macros, runtime-branch predicates, functions and daemon fields must be known: 

- MHD_USE_THREADS (preprocessor macro): large portions of the function are conditionally compiled under this macro. Whether those blocks exist at all depends on this macro; absent/present changes what code can be reached. 

- MHD_D_IS_USING_THREAD_PER_CONN_ (macro/function): this runtime predicate selects the thread-per-connection path versus the single-thread handling path. To decide if either branch (and its returns/cleanup) is ever executable you must know the definition/semantics of this symbol.

- MHD_create_named_thread_ (and underlying MHD_create_thread_): success of this call causes an immediate return (MHD_YES). To know whether the code after the successful-thread branch can be executed (or is unreachable in practice) you must know the possible return values and success/failure conditions of this symbol.

- EPOLL_SUPPORT (preprocessor macro): the entire epoll-handling code is conditional on this macro. Its presence/absence changes which return paths exist, so it is essential for reachability analysis.

- MHD_D_IS_USING_EPOLL_ (macro/function): at runtime this predicate selects the epoll vs non-epoll path. Whether the epoll branches (which contain early returns) can ever be taken depends on this symbol’s definition/behavior.

- MHD_USE_TURBO (flag constant) and daemon->options (field): within the epoll path the MHD_USE_TURBO option selects the EDLL_insert fast-path (with immediate return) versus the epoll_ctl path. To decide if one of these epoll branches is impossible for all configurations you need these definitions and how daemon->options is set.

- epoll_ctl (system call) and EPOLL_CTL_ADD / epoll event flags: the code checks the return of epoll_ctl and returns on success; understanding whether epoll_ctl can ever succeed (and thus make later cleanup unreachable) requires knowledge of the call semantics and the constants used.

- MHD_pool_create and MHD_pool_destroy: pool creation success vs failure controls whether the function enters the main processing block (with multiple early returns) or immediately goes to the final cleanup path. Knowing the possible return values of MHD_pool_create is necessary to determine if either the success or failure branch is unreachable.

- daemon->connection_limit and daemon->connections (fields): the code checks connection limit under a mutex and either proceeds or takes the connection-limit failure path. To judge reachability of the limit-failure branch (and consequent cleanup) you must know how these fields can be initialized/modified.

- DLL_insert / XDLL_insert / EDLL_insert and corresponding remove functions: these list-manipulation calls bracket successful connection insertion and are paired with removal in cleanup. If any of these operations are defined as no-ops or are conditionally compiled away, some cleanup code might become unreachable; their semantics affect which code paths can actually execute.

- daemon->notify_connection (field) and its semantics: presence or always-null of this callback changes whether the notify_connection calls are reachable. If this field is guaranteed NULL (or non-NULL) by construction, the corresponding branches would be unreachable/exclusively used.

In short: to prove whether any portion of new_connection_process_ is unreachable for all possible builds and runtime states you must know the compile-time feature macros (MHD_USE_THREADS, EPOLL_SUPPORT), the runtime selection predicates/macros (MHD_D_IS_USING_THREAD_PER_CONN_, MHD_D_IS_USING_EPOLL_), option flags (MHD_USE_TURBO + daemon->options), and the behaviors/return semantics of the key functions and daemon fields that control the branching (MHD_create_named_thread_, epoll_ctl, MHD_pool_create, connection counters, list-insert/remove and notify_connection). Without these symbols and their definitions/semantics you cannot conclude whether any branch is impossible and thus unreachable under MISRA criteria.
